# PRD: Dedicated Meeting Computer Agent

## 1. Product summary

### Product name

**Meeting Computer Agent**
Working name: **Agent Workstation**

### One-line description

A web-controlled AI teammate that runs on a dedicated laptop, joins Google Meet as a participant, listens to the meeting, speaks out loud, shares its screen, reads local workspace files, browses websites, and creates Trello tasks.

### Core idea

The system gives a dedicated physical computer to an AI agent. The agent uses that computer like a teammate: it joins meetings, listens, speaks, opens documents, browses websites, and creates product-management tasks.

For the hackathon MVP, the most important proof is not “the agent can do everything.” The most important proof is:

> The agent can join a Google Meet call as a participant, hear the conversation, speak naturally, and later perform visible work from that meeting context.

---

## 2. MVP priority

### Phase 0: Voice meeting agent first

The first version should focus only on:

1. User pastes a Google Meet link into the web app.
2. Dedicated Mac receives the meeting link.
3. Mac opens Chrome and joins the Google Meet using an agent-only account.
4. Agent can hear meeting audio.
5. Agent can speak back into the meeting.
6. Agent waits for silence before speaking.
7. Agent responds naturally when it believes someone is asking it something.

This phase should not yet include Trello, file reading, browsing, or screen sharing unless the voice foundation is stable.

### Why this comes first

If the agent cannot reliably join, hear, and speak, then file reading, browsing, and Trello automation will not feel like a real meeting agent. The voice/meeting loop is the foundation.

Gemini Live is a good candidate for this because the Live API is designed for low-latency realtime voice interactions, and it supports tool/function calling once you later add browser, file, and Trello tools.

