## 4. Main demo story

A team joins a Google Meet call. The AI agent joins as a participant from its own account.

Someone says:

> “Can you help us review this project brief and create execution tasks?”

The agent waits for a pause, responds out loud, opens the project brief from its dedicated workspace, summarizes it, discusses the plan, browses a website for extra context, creates Trello cards, and opens the Trello board while sharing its screen.

---

## 5. Product goals

### Goal 1: Prove the “AI teammate in a meeting” experience

The agent should feel like an actual meeting participant, not just a chatbot.

### Goal 2: Prove dedicated computer use

The agent should operate from a real dedicated laptop with its own browser, accounts, workspace folder, and screen.

### Goal 3: Prove autonomous workflow execution

After the meeting discussion, the agent should be able to turn conversation and documents into concrete output, such as Trello tasks.

### Goal 4: Keep the MVP simple enough to work

The first working version should avoid unnecessary complexity: no multi-worker system, no automatic calendar joining, no complex user permissions, no production-grade audit logs.

---

## 6. Non-goals for MVP

The first MVP will not support:

* Multiple agent laptops
* Automatic calendar-based meeting joining
* Slack/Teams/Zoom support
* Native desktop app control
* Full file-system access
* Production-grade permission management
* Human approval flows
* Full meeting transcript and audit log
* Complex Trello task metadata
* Multi-agent reasoning with many independent agents
* Production security hardening
* Support for all websites and all UI states

